WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.150 --> 00:00:02.010
- On December 1st, 2022,

00:00:02.010 --> 00:00:04.440
the journal "Nature"
published a cover story

00:00:04.440 --> 00:00:06.900
about a holographic wormhole.

00:00:06.900 --> 00:00:09.600
It was purportedly created
inside a quantum computer

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:13.440
to probe the intersection of
quantum mechanics and gravity.

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:17.940
The story kicked off a frenzy
of tweets and news headlines.

00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:19.920
- Nobody has seen the wormhole.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:21.630
Nobody has produced one.

00:00:21.630 --> 00:00:23.010
- Well, we'll
take the world's best

00:00:23.010 --> 00:00:25.440
quantum computer and
see if we can map that

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:26.700
into building the wormhole.

00:00:26.700 --> 00:00:29.160
- The wormhole becomes
traversable, it opens.

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:30.663
You really can go through.

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:35.215
- Bull (beep).
(host laughing)

00:00:35.215 --> 00:00:36.048
(magnets clicking)

00:00:36.048 --> 00:00:37.780
- This video is sponsored by Shopify.

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:41.100
The problem was, of course,

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:43.470
that no wormhole had been created.

00:00:43.470 --> 00:00:44.580
- It feeds on itself, right?

00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:46.380
When one story starts,

00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:48.720
then other media outlets grab hold of it

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:50.580
and so it spreads very, very quickly.

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:52.800
- What actually happened is that a super,

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:54.930
a quantum computer is built

00:00:54.930 --> 00:00:56.730
and within this quantum computer,

00:00:56.730 --> 00:00:58.530
you can do some calculations.

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:02.520
Calculations that can
be done with my iPhone

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:06.300
because all the most powerful
quantum computers today,

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:07.650
at most do calculations

00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:09.870
that can easily be done on my iPhone.

00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:11.460
- You basically have something

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:14.670
that represents the
mathematics of a wormhole.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:16.470
But the way the story was sold, of course,

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:19.680
is that in doing this,
whatever calculation they did,

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:22.260
they had created the wormhole.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.397
- They say so in the same
sense in which I could say,

00:01:24.397 --> 00:01:27.877
"Look, my children has built a rocket

00:01:27.877 --> 00:01:29.670
"that goes to the moon."

00:01:29.670 --> 00:01:32.223
Say, "Wow, what kind of child you have?

00:01:33.247 --> 00:01:34.497
"Yeah, here it is."

00:01:34.497 --> 00:01:38.460
And I show you a little
sketch on a piece of paper

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:40.827
when there is a drawing of
a rocket going to the moon

00:01:40.827 --> 00:01:41.940
and say, "Look!"

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:44.970
So what the quantum computer
has done is exactly that.

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:49.920
There's a little sketch of what
could be perhaps a warm hole

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:53.040
in some hypothetical theory,
which is probably wrong.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:54.000
Is this interesting?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.230
Yes, it is interesting

00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:57.150
because the fact that
with quantum computers

00:01:57.150 --> 00:01:59.820
you can do these things
mean that quantum computers,

00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:01.740
a little bit, sort of begin working.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:04.650
So people get excited about
that and then they go out

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:08.707
and tell to the world, "Oh,
we've created a wormhole

00:02:08.707 --> 00:02:09.987
"in a quantum computer,"

00:02:10.950 --> 00:02:13.200
over overemphasizing the wormhole,

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:17.010
which probably don't exist,
the theory being used of that,

00:02:17.010 --> 00:02:18.480
which probably is wrong,

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:20.310
and the utility of quantum computers,

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:21.870
which is not yet there.

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:24.180
So that's an example of bad communication,

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:25.350
very bad communication.

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:26.340
I was embarrassed,

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:28.680
I was angry with my
colleagues who did that.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:30.420
- To me, it looks like the source

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:32.820
of this problem is bad incentives.

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:35.370
Scientists need to secure
funding for their research

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:37.410
and increasingly that depends on

00:02:37.410 --> 00:02:39.630
attracting public attention to their work.

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:41.643
- It's just become part
of the culture of science,

00:02:41.643 --> 00:02:44.310
that it's expected that you will have some

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:46.080
sort of media attention

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.470
and to get that attention,
you have to sell your science

00:02:49.470 --> 00:02:52.560
and often it's not the
result of the science

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:55.290
that is the story, it's something else.

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:57.690
- Universities seek to promote themselves

00:02:57.690 --> 00:03:00.990
to attract students and
bolster their reputations.

00:03:00.990 --> 00:03:03.420
- And nowhere in the scientific method is,

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.450
and you release a press release,

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:09.390
but it's just become part of the norm now.

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:13.830
- Press releases simplify and
may overstate the research

00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:15.510
and journalists just want to get

00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:18.510
as many clicks on their
stories as they can.

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:21.090
The end result of this incentivized game

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:23.640
of telephone can be oversimplified

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:28.530
sensationalized headlines,
science that is just plain wrong.

00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:30.210
Now, I myself have been guilty

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:32.070
of over-hyping a science story.

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:35.760
Back in 2014, I made a video
about the bicep two experiment.

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:38.340
So this is one of the hugest discoveries

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:40.020
in science of all time.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.690
Researchers reportedly
detected polarization

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:45.270
in the cosmic microwave
background radiation.

00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:48.360
Allegedly it was caused by
gravitational fluctuations

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.660
just a fraction of a
second after the big bang.

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:54.300
The result was considered
the first real evidence

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:55.710
of the quantum nature of gravity

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:59.280
and a smoking gun for inflation theory.

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:01.830
Experimenters even surprised Andre Lind,

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:05.100
one of the founders of
inflation theory with the news.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:07.830
- Let's just hope that it is not a trick.

00:04:07.830 --> 00:04:10.683
I always leave with this feeling,

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.320
what if I'm tricked?

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:18.320
What if I believe in this
just because it is beautiful?

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:22.410
- Unfortunately, further
observations showed

00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:24.960
that it was likely just
dust in our own galaxy

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:27.000
rather than primordial gravitational waves

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.760
that created the polarization in the CMB.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:31.830
So I took down my video

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:34.800
and to this day I am
wary about making videos

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:37.020
about breaking science news.

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:40.230
Like any type of breaking news,
there is a high probability

00:04:40.230 --> 00:04:42.780
that early reports will
turn out to be wrong.

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:44.910
Just a few months ago,
a paper was uploaded

00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:46.710
to the Archive Pre-print Server

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.440
claiming to have discovered
the first room temperature

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:51.750
ambient pressure superconductor.

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:55.230
This again triggered a
flood of media attention.

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:57.660
- [Reporter] A monumental breakthrough,

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:01.293
room temperature superconductor LK99.

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:03.870
- One of the most important scientific

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:06.090
breakthroughs of the 21st century.

00:05:06.090 --> 00:05:09.840
- If the discovery were real,
it would've been a big deal.

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:11.610
- The room temperature
superconductor stuff,

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:15.300
of course, is such a
dream 'cause if it worked,

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:18.390
it would revolutionize everything, right?

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:20.760
Transmission of energy,
that kind of stuff.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.340
The world would be different if it worked.

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:25.710
- But even before attempts
to replicate the material

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:27.180
and its properties failed,

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:30.030
there were clear signs
that the claim was false.

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:32.400
In the only published
plot showing resistivity

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:35.880
versus temperature, the
resistivity did not drop to zero

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:39.210
as you'd expect at the
supposed critical temperature.

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:42.420
Instead, it continued to
decrease below this value.

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:44.640
Plus the resistivity
scale was given in units

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:47.670
of 10 to the minus two ohm centimeters.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:49.890
On that scale, any ordinary conductor

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:52.200
would appear to have zero resistivity.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:53.940
Copper's resistivity, for example,

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:57.360
is on the order of 10 to the
minus six ohm centimeters.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:00.090
A video showed the material
apparently levitating

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:03.210
above a permanent magnet
in a supposed demonstration

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:04.830
of the Meisner effect.

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.020
But in that same video, the material

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:08.820
also sticks to the magnet,

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:11.850
something a superconductor would not do.

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:14.250
And finally there is this plot,

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:16.200
showing that over the
past a hundred years,

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:18.150
scientists have found new materials

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:20.910
with progressively higher
critical temperatures.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:24.210
But as of now, all the
highest temperature materials

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:26.790
only super conduct at very high pressures.

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:29.850
For an ambient pressure room
temperature superconductor,

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:32.040
we would need a jump
in critical temperature

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:35.370
of around 125 degrees Celsius.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:37.920
That's a lot and this brings up the point

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:41.070
that it is the most unexpected
and surprising results

00:06:41.070 --> 00:06:42.930
that get the most attention,

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:44.970
but it is also these very same results

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:47.610
that are the most likely to be false.

00:06:47.610 --> 00:06:49.980
In social science, it's
been shown that studies

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:51.990
that later fail to be replicated,

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:55.560
receive on average 153 more citations

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:57.810
than studies that can be replicated.

00:06:57.810 --> 00:06:59.570
Similar buzz surrounds faulty research

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:01.170
in the physical sciences.

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:03.060
- The Italians, I'm Italian,

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:06.240
came out announcing into
the world some time ago

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:08.010
that the neutrino was faster than light

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:11.430
and then measured it and
it turned out to be a plug

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:13.500
that was not fitting well

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:16.230
and so the entire machine
was not working well.

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:18.030
- When the truth is discovered,

00:07:18.030 --> 00:07:21.660
it rarely gets as much attention
as the original finding.

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:23.317
- The fallout where everybody was going,

00:07:23.317 --> 00:07:25.957
"Oh, well this doesn't work
and this doesn't look right

00:07:25.957 --> 00:07:27.757
"and there's no way this material can do

00:07:27.757 --> 00:07:29.070
"what they say it's doing."

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:31.380
That sort of fizzles in the background,

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:33.630
it doesn't get the same media attention.

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:35.107
- There is the apt saying,

00:07:35.107 --> 00:07:36.817
"A lie can travel around the world

00:07:36.817 --> 00:07:39.780
"while the truth is still
putting on its shoes."

00:07:39.780 --> 00:07:41.730
But that saying might need to be updated

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:44.430
in the age of social
media when lies now have

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:46.620
an even greater advantage.

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:50.220
Do you think it's a bigger
problem now than it used to be?

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:52.590
- I must admit that I
think it's getting worse.

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:53.760
I think there's a feeling

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:57.150
that you've got to change the world

00:07:57.150 --> 00:07:59.250
to be noticed by the media.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.560
- Over-hyping science
discoveries can give people

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:04.143
a false sense of how science works.

00:08:05.100 --> 00:08:08.130
If that latest discovery I hear
about turns out to be false,

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:10.050
what else could be untrue?

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:12.930
- People keep telling me
that cosmology's in crisis

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:15.210
and all this kind of stuff
because that's the kind of stories

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:16.680
they hear in the media.

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:17.617
Eventually people will say,

00:08:17.617 --> 00:08:20.137
"Well, why are we funding these things

00:08:20.137 --> 00:08:22.170
"if it's always just turmoil?"

00:08:22.170 --> 00:08:24.420
- Making bold unsubstantiated claims

00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:27.120
also reduces trust in scientists.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:30.360
- So we are enlarging a little bit.

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:34.980
The conversation here is not
just single pieces of news.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.773
I think there are entire
fields which are hyped.

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:42.390
- Wait, entire fields of science that are-

00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:43.590
- Yes.
- Hyped.

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:44.423
- Yes.

00:08:44.423 --> 00:08:45.870
- But aren't really legit

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:50.040
or just they're all hot air or...

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:51.300
- Oh no, no, they're not hot air.

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:53.610
- [Host] Fusion, fusion's big in the news.

00:08:53.610 --> 00:08:54.870
People think it's close, right?

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:55.703
There's startups,

00:08:55.703 --> 00:08:57.390
there's people getting
billions of dollars.

00:08:57.390 --> 00:08:59.610
- Exactly, I don't know
where we are there.

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:01.170
Again, it's not my field,

00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:04.058
but there was one particular announcement,

00:09:04.058 --> 00:09:04.891
what is it?

00:09:04.891 --> 00:09:05.724
One year ago or something.

00:09:05.724 --> 00:09:07.290
- [Host] I remember this announcement.

00:09:07.290 --> 00:09:10.770
- Scientists have produced
a nuclear fusion reaction

00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:13.710
