00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:45.720
And now back to science hype.

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:48.210
Science is interesting in
that you can divide it up

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:50.490
into basically two categories.

00:12:50.490 --> 00:12:53.100
One is an established body of knowledge

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:56.850
and the other is speculations,
things that might be true,

00:12:56.850 --> 00:12:59.370
but we don't really have any
solid evidence for them yet.

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:02.790
And because there can be
an infinity of bad ideas

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:03.990
and only one truth,

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:07.260
most of these speculations
are likely wrong.

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:09.540
But the way certain topics
are discussed in the media,

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:11.100
it may be impossible to tell

00:13:11.100 --> 00:13:13.500
if they're part of the
established body of knowledge

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:16.110
or just very fanciful speculation.

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:17.737
- There are too many
books out there saying,

00:13:17.737 --> 00:13:18.877
"We have understood that the world's

00:13:18.877 --> 00:13:21.120
"made by strings and string theory."

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.100
It's not true, not at all.

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:24.780
We have not understood that the world

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:26.160
is described as string theory.

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:28.530
We have a very interesting
tentative theory,

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:30.840
which is string theory,
which has that some success

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:34.320
and some failures and that's interesting.

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:38.430
If you want to tell about this research,

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.050
do tell about this research,

00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:42.010
but don't tell people that

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:46.440
it's what we have learned about the world.

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:48.123
- One question I have is,

00:13:50.988 --> 00:13:53.100
how do we get past the
over-hyping of science?

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:55.410
Because it seems like the system is set up

00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:57.540
to reward over-hyping.

00:13:57.540 --> 00:13:59.670
It rewards the journalists
'cause they get the clicks.

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:00.840
It rewards the scientists,

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:03.150
they may get the money or the attention.

00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:05.250
So I don't know, I'm kind of curious

00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:08.160
whether a solution is possible.

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:10.263
- Yeah, I think there is one,

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:13.420
and it's exactly what you're doing.

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:18.510
By talking about the fact

00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:21.090
that there is a risk of overhyping.

00:14:21.090 --> 00:14:22.327
If I can go out and say,

00:14:22.327 --> 00:14:25.980
"Oh, my quantum computer
produced a wormhole,"

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:30.000
and nobody says anything,
that's a problem.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.400
If we talk about the risk of over-hyping,

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:36.510
if we talk about the
risk of presenting ideas,

00:14:36.510 --> 00:14:38.610
theories, radical results,

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:42.720
which are very, very tentative, as solid,

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:47.720
then we sort of immunize
ourself against this danger.

00:14:47.910 --> 00:14:49.380
- Science is not presented on the news

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:51.680
like sport is presented on the news.

00:14:51.680 --> 00:14:54.120
At the end of the news, you
get 10 minutes of sports

00:14:54.120 --> 00:14:55.470
where they will talk about the fact

00:14:55.470 --> 00:14:57.600
that somebody kicked a
ball around in a field

00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:59.460
and it's not that particularly important.

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:00.870
So you get the full rundown

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:03.810
of lots of bits and
pieces of what's going on.

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:05.880
But to get a science story,

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:07.887
it has to be Earth
shattering kind of thing.

00:15:07.887 --> 00:15:10.320
It has to be a big story.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:14.790
What many scientists would
like is this larger picture

00:15:14.790 --> 00:15:18.810
of the fact that the entire
enterprise is moving forward.

00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:20.850
That there are lots of things happening

00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:24.360
and we definitely know more
tomorrow than we do today,

00:15:24.360 --> 00:15:27.750
but that's not the way that it
gets picked up by the media.

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:30.450
- Well, ultimately, almost
everyone is incentivized

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:32.970
to sensationalize scientific findings.

00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:34.650
So I think it's important to remember that

00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:37.650
anytime you hear a
science story on the news,

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:39.690
surprising, unexpected results

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:42.270
that have not been
independently replicated,

00:15:42.270 --> 00:15:45.300
they are more likely than not to be wrong.

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:47.880
But despite this, I remain
convinced that science

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:50.370
is the best way to get at the truth.

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:52.650
I mean, sure, in the short term,

00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:54.030
some may seek the spotlight

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:55.830
by rushing the data analysis,

00:15:55.830 --> 00:15:59.250
overstating results or
circumventing peer review.

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:00.900
but in the long term,

00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:04.200
that is not going to
win you the Nobel Prize.

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:06.900
The bold claims, mistakes and dead ends,

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:09.300
they will fade into oblivion

00:16:09.300 --> 00:16:12.150
and only sound science
that is vigorously tested

00:16:12.150 --> 00:16:13.950
and independently validated,

00:16:13.950 --> 00:16:17.673
that is what makes it into the
accepted body of knowledge.

